# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geneve-encapsulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] Encapsulation and deencapsulation allow the design of modular communication protocols so to logically separate the function of each communications layer, and abstract the structure of the communicated information over the other communications layers.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] These two processes are common features of the computer-networking models and protocol suites, like in the OSI model and internet protocol suite.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] However, encapsulation/deencapsulation processes can also serve as malicious features like in the tunneling protocols.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] For example, in the IP suite, the contents of a web page are encapsulated with an HTTP header, then by a TCP header, an IP header, and, finally, by a frame header and trailer.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] The frame is forwarded to the destination node as a stream of bits, where it is decapsulated into the respective PDUs and interpreted at each layer by the receiving node.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] The result of encapsulation is that each lower-layer provides a service to the layer or layers above it, while at the same time each layer communicates with its corresponding layer on the receiving node.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] These are known as adjacent-layer interaction and same-layer interaction, respectively.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] In discussions of encapsulation, the more abstract layer is often called the upper-layer protocol while the more specific layer is called the lower-layer protocol.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/encapsulation-networking] Sometimes, however, the terms upper-layer protocols and lower-layer protocols are used to describe the layers above and below IP.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-network-virtualization-encapsulation] Open vSwitch is an example of a software-based virtual network switch that supports Geneve overlay networks.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-network-virtualization-encapsulation] It is also supported by AWS Gateway Load Balancers.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-routing-encapsulation] Based on the principles of protocol layering in OSI, protocol encapsulation, not specifically GRE, breaks the layering order.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-routing-encapsulation] It may be viewed as a separator between two different protocol stacks, one acting as a carrier for another.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-routing-encapsulation] GRE packets that are encapsulated within IP directly, use IP protocol type 47 in the IPv4 header's *Protocol* field or the IPv6 header's *Next Header* field.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-routing-encapsulation] For performance reasons, GRE can also be encapsulated in UDP packets.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/generic-routing-encapsulation] Better throughput may be achieved by using Equal-cost multi-path routing.
