[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] An **overlay network** is a logical computer network that is layered on top of a physical network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The concept of overlay networking is distinct from the traditional model of OSI layered networks, and almost always assumes that the underlay network is an IP network of some kind.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Some examples of overlay networking technologies are, VXLAN, BGP VPNs, and IP-over-IP technologies, such as GRE, IPSEC tunnels, or SD-WAN.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Nodes in an overlay network can be thought of as being connected by logical links, each of which corresponds to a path, perhaps through many physical links, in the underlying network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] For example, distributed systems such as peer-to-peer networks are overlay networks because their nodes form networks over existing network connections.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The Internet was originally built as an overlay upon the telephone network, while today (through the advent of VoIP), the telephone network is increasingly turning into an overlay network built on top of the Internet.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Overlay networks have a certain set of attributes, including separation of logical addressing, security and quality of service.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Other optional attributes include resiliency, encryption and bandwidth control.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Guaranteeing bandwidth through marking traffic has multiple solutions, including IntServ and DiffServ.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] IntServ requires per-flow tracking and consequently causes scaling issues in routing platforms.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] DiffServ has been widely deployed in many operators as a method to differentiate traffic types.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] DiffServ itself provides no guarantee of throughput; it does allow the network operator to decide which traffic is higher priority, and hence will be forwarded first in congestion situations.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Overlay networks implement a much finer granularity of quality of service, allowing enterprise users to decide on an application and user or site basis which traffic should be prioritized.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Many telcos use overlay networks to provide services over their physical infrastructure.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] In the networks that connect physically diverse sites (wide area networks, WANs), one common overlay network technology is BGP VPNs.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] These VPNs are provided in the form of a service to enterprises to connect their own sites and applications.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The advantage of these kinds of overlay networks is that the telecom operator does not need to manage addressing or other enterprise-specific network attributes.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] From an enterprise point of view, while an overlay VPN service configured by the operator might fulfill their basic connectivity requirements, SD-WAN overlay networks offer additional flexibility.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The Internet is the basis for more overlaid networks that can be constructed in order to permit routing of messages to destinations not specified by an IP address.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] For example, distributed hash tables can be used to route messages to a node having a specific logical address, whose IP address is not known in advance.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Overlay networks can be incrementally deployed at end-user sites or on hosts running the overlay protocol software, without cooperation from Internet service providers.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The overlay has no control over how packets are routed in the underlying network between two overlay nodes, but it can control, for example, the sequence of overlay nodes a message traverses before reaching its destination.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The objective of resilience in telecommunications networks is to enable automated recovery during failure events in order to maintain a wanted service level or availability.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] As telecommunications networks are built in a layered fashion, resilience can be used in the physical, optical, IP or session to application layers.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Each layer relies on the resilience features of the layer below it.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Overlay IP networks in the form of SD-WAN services therefore rely on the physical, optical and underlying IP services they are transported over.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Application-layer overlays depend on all the layers below them.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The advantage of overlays is that they are more flexible and programmable than traditional network infrastructure, which can outweigh the disadvantages of additional latency, complexity and bandwidth overheads.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] The limited deployment of IP multicast, a best-effort network-layer multicast protocol, has led to considerable interest in alternate approaches that are implemented at the application layer in accordance with the end-to-end principle.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] In an overlay or end-system multicast approach, participating peers organize themselves into an overlay topology for data delivery.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] Each edge in this topology corresponds to a unicast path between two end-systems or peers in the underlying internet.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/overlay-network] All multicast-related functionality is implemented at the peers instead of at routers, and the goal of the multicast protocol is to construct and maintain an efficient overlay for data transmission.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In computer networks, a **tunneling protocol** is a communication protocol that allows for the movement of data from one network to another.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] They can, for example, allow private communications to be sent across a public network (such as the Internet), or for one network protocol to be carried over an incompatible network, through a process called encapsulation.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Because tunneling involves repackaging the traffic data into a different form, perhaps with encryption as standard, it can hide the nature of the traffic that is run through a tunnel.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling protocols work by using the data portion of a packet (the payload) to carry the packets that actually provide the service.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling uses a layered protocol model such as those of the OSI or TCP/IP protocol suite, but usually violates the layering when using the payload to carry a service not normally provided by the network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Typically, the delivery protocol operates at an equal or higher level in the layered model than the payload protocol.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] A tunneling protocol may, for example, allow a foreign protocol to run over a network that does not support that particular protocol, such as running IPv6 over IPv4.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Another important use is to provide services that are impractical or unsafe to be offered using only the underlying network services, such as providing a corporate network address to a remote user whose physical network address is not part of the corporate network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Users can also use tunneling to "sneak through" a firewall, using a protocol that the firewall would normally block, but "wrapped" inside a protocol that the firewall does not block, such as HTTP.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] If the firewall policy does not specifically exclude this kind of "wrapping", this trick can function to get around the intended firewall policy (or any set of interlocked firewall policies).
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Another HTTP-based tunneling method uses the HTTP CONNECT method/command.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] A client issues the HTTP CONNECT command to an HTTP proxy.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The proxy then makes a TCP connection to a particular server:port, and relays data between that server:port and the client connection.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Because this creates a security hole, CONNECT-capable HTTP proxies commonly restrict access to the CONNECT method.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The proxy allows connections only to specific ports, such as 443 for HTTPS.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Other tunneling methods able to bypass network firewalls make use of different protocols such as DNS, MQTT, and SMS.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] As an example of network layer over network layer, Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE), a protocol running over IP (IP protocol number 47), often serves to carry IP packets, with RFC 1918 private addresses, over the Internet using delivery packets with public IP addresses.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In this case, the delivery and payload protocols are the same, but the payload addresses are incompatible with those of the delivery network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] It is also possible to establish a connection using the data link layer.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) allows the transmission of frames between two nodes.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] A tunnel is not encrypted by default: the TCP/IP protocol chosen determines the level of security.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] SSH uses port 22 to enable data encryption of payloads being transmitted over a public network (such as the Internet) connection, thereby providing VPN functionality.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] IPsec has an end-to-end Transport Mode, but can also operate in a tunneling mode through a trusted security gateway.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] To understand a particular protocol stack imposed by tunneling, network engineers must understand both the payload and delivery protocol sets.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The throughput of a TCP‑over‑TCP connection can be degraded because the control loops in the inner and outer TCPs interfere destructively with each other.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Because TCP is designed to guarantee in‑order and complete packet delivery, the outer TCP masks the connection's health from the inner TCP.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In normal TCP operation, packet loss is detected when the receiver replies with duplicate ACKs to a packet received before the missing packet in the sequence.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In response, the sender retransmits the lost packet and halves the Congestion Window (CWND).
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In TCP‑over‑TCP, the outer TCP handles lost packets normally through retransmission and CWND reduction.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Still, since the inner TCP has not received any information indicating latency in the connection, it continues to transmit packets at the rate currently governed by its CWND.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP’s CWND is greater than the outer TCP’s, the outer TCP’s send buffer eventually fills.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] As the buffer inflates, packets experience longer and more variable queueing delays before transmission, thereby increasing the outer TCP’s measured round-trip time (RTT) and RTT variability.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] This inflates its retransmission timeout (RTO).
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Once the send buffer becomes full, the tunnel process can no longer forward inner‑TCP ACKs, so the inner TCP stops receiving acknowledgments entirely.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP is no longer receiving ACKs, its RTO expires, causing it to retransmit the oldest unacknowledged segment and double its RTO.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The inner TCP’s RTO then grows exponentially because it doubles with every timeout, and no ACKs are received to reset it.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] The result of a TCP meltdown is an outer TCP with a severely reduced CWND, an inflated RTO, and a full send buffer.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] This indicates that the inner TCP cannot write and that ACKs are not being sent in either direction.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] A *Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel* consists of an encrypted tunnel created through an SSH protocol connection.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Users may set up SSH tunnels to transfer unencrypted traffic over a network through an encrypted channel.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] It is a software-based approach to network security and the result is transparent encryption.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] For example, Microsoft Windows machines can share files using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol, a non-encrypted protocol.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] If one were to mount a Microsoft Windows file-system remotely through the Internet, someone snooping on the connection could see transferred files.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] To mount the Windows file-system securely, one can establish a SSH tunnel that routes all SMB traffic to the remote fileserver through an encrypted channel.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Even though the SMB protocol itself contains no encryption, the encrypted SSH channel through which it travels offers security.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Once an SSH connection has been established, the tunnel starts with SSH listening to a port on the remote or local host.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Any connections to it are forwarded to the specified address and port originating from the opposing (remote or local, as previously) host.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Naturally, this wrapping and unwrapping also occurs in the reverse direction of the bidirectional tunnel.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] SSH tunnels provide a means to bypass firewalls that prohibit certain Internet services – so long as a site allows outgoing connections.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] For example, an organization may prohibit a user from accessing Internet web pages (port 80) directly without passing through the organization's proxy filter (which provides the organization with a means of monitoring and controlling what the user sees through the web).
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] But users may not wish to have their web traffic monitored or blocked by the organisation's proxy filter.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] If users can connect to an external SSH server, they can create an SSH tunnel to forward a given port on their local machine to port 80 on a remote web server.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Some SSH clients support dynamic port forwarding that allows the user to create a SOCKS 4/5 proxy.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In this case users can configure their applications to use their local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] This gives more flexibility than creating an SSH tunnel to a single port as previously described.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] SOCKS can free the user from the limitations of connecting only to a predefined remote port and server.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] If an application does not support SOCKS, a proxifier can be used to redirect the application to the local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Some proxifiers, such as Proxycap, support SSH directly, thus avoiding the need for an SSH client.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In recent versions of OpenSSH it is even allowed to create layer 2 or layer 3 tunnels if both ends have enabled such tunneling capabilities.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] This creates `tun` (layer 3, default) or `tap` (layer 2) virtual interfaces on both ends of the connection.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] This allows normal network management and routing to be used, and when used on routers, the traffic for an entire subnetwork can be tunneled.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] A pair of `tap` virtual interfaces function like an Ethernet cable connecting both ends of the connection and can join kernel bridges.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] Over the years, tunneling and data encapsulation have in very rare cases been adopted for malicious reasons, in order to maliciously communicate outside of a protected network.
[src:geneve-encapsulation/tunneling-protocol] In this context, known tunnels involve protocols such as HTTP, SSH, DNS, MQTT.
